\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The ontological sextet has been specialised into several flavours, all called \{ upper-level | top-level | foundational \}^[Please select the term you like best.] ontologies, e.g., UFO [@Guizzardi:2015ky], SUMO [@Niles:2001], YAMAYATO [@Mizoguchi:2010vv], BFO [@Grenon2004], DOLCE [@Masolo2002] and more, and with their similarities and differences between them [@Jansen2008]. Not all of them are intended to provide for a complete foundation as UFO and BFO do; several are primarily developed for facilitating particular philosophical theories (DOLCE), others (YAMAYATO, SUMO) are the result of research into mentioned theories. No matter the reason for their existence, they all assume a certain philosophical viewpoint with the purpose to accurately describe categories that exist in reality according to their viewpoint. We consider this the *philosophical cornerstone* that is required to produce semantics that are faithful to reality. We thus defend that the semantic validity of any proposition can only be assessed if and only if the underlying ontological commitment can be referred to. Furthermore, any assessment towards semantic interoperability of two semantic theories cannot be made without an assessment of the similarity between their underlying ontological commitments. Note, however, that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93We look to (\u8230\'85) Ontology not in order to know *what there is*, but in order to know what a given remark or doctrine, ours or someone else\u8217\'92s, *says* there is\u8221\'94 [@Quine:1953er]. It then remains the responsibility of the (domain) analyst or ontology engineer to select the viewpoint that is most appropriate for its purpose, in order to select the modelling language that describes the types of things that exist in the domain of application the most accurate.}
